1. 28. [ao] aum nola decima-legione. Observa the excellence os this speech. It is quiet and ratiocinativa (and therefore, as given, almost entirely retains the regular oblique tenses); yet the topics are of the unquestionable character which alone can convince a blind panic. After displaying these briefly but sully, he returns to his favourite mode os thought and expression ;—there will be no mutiny, because he has not deserved any (chap. 14, init), and he ends by a bold rhetorical declaration that he is ready to march with the tenth legion only.
